"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754788","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>No final decisions have been taken on the UK’s post-Brexit Immigration system. We are considering the options for our future immigration system very carefully. It is important that we understand the impacts on the different sectors of the economy and the labour market. We will, therefore, ensure that businesses and communities have the opportunity to contribute their views. We will build a comprehensive picture of the needs and interests of all parts of the UK and look to develop a system which works for all.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T14:28:24.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754788/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754788/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Visas: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department plans to implement the recommendation in the Recruitment and Employment Confederation's report, Building the Post-Brexit Immigration System, published in June 2017, on introducing seasonal temporary work visas.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","6567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754789","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","6645 ; 6646","2017-09-11T14:21:21.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754789/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754789/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Entry Clearances: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many marriage visa applications from (a) Pakistan, (b) Indian, (c) Bangladeshi and (d) American nationals were overturned on appeal in (i) 2014, (ii) 2015 and (iii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Naz Shah","Bradford West","Naz Shah","6653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754790","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Information on the number of Family: Partner applications, and the number of cases resolved (i.e. decisions, of which how many were granted or refused), is published quarterly. This is avalable at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2017/list-of-tables#visas" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2017/list-of-tables#visas</a></p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to separately identify applications made or decided under the previous or new rules. Not all of the family route statistics from 9 July 2012 onwards relate to the new Immigration Rules. Further details are provided in the ‘Family’ section of the User Guide to Home Office Immigration Statistics, available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/user-guide-to-home-office-immigration-statistics--9" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/user-guide-to-home-office-immigration-statistics--9</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","6648 ; 6649 ; 6650 ; 6651 ; 6652","2017-09-11T14:12:01.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754790/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754790/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Entry Clearances: Bangladesh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many marriage visa applications from Bangladeshi nationals her Department received in (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016; and how many of those applications were (i) accepted, (ii) rejected and (iii) rejected for failing to meet the income threshold requirement in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Naz Shah","Bradford West","Naz Shah","6647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754791","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The drugs licensing online system is available on request.</p><p> </p><p>The bidding process for applications for the Modern Slavery Innovation Fund in October last year included an offer in the bidding document to provide documents in Welsh on request.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring that the needs of Welsh language speakers are recognised and met, in accordance with the requirements of departmental Welsh Language Schemes.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-05T08:08:57.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754791/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754791/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Home Office: Welsh Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which online services provided by her Department are available in the Welsh language on request only.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","6660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754792","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Businesses who are licensed sponsors may already directly assign certificates of sponsorship to workers. The exception is where the Tier 2 (General) annual limit applies, in which cases employers must request certificates under a monthly allocation. This ensures that places go to workers with the skills most in need and who will make the greatest economic contributions.</p><p>The entity sponsoring the worker needs to be sufficiently aware of their activities – that means the employer, rather than a representative body, is best suited to be the sponsor.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T13:25:59.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754792/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754792/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Visas: Sponsorship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of allowing businesses and their representative bodies who obtain licensed sponsor status the ability to issue directly certificates of sponsorship for workers.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","6654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754793","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>Places of safety are defined in the Mental Health Act 1983 and include hospitals, care homes for mentally disordered persons, police stations, specified local service authority residential accommodation and any other suitable place the occupier of which is willing temporarily to receive the patient.</p><p>Specific guidance to police officers on the availability of places of safety in their areas is a local matter. Local partnerships should have established policy or protocols on the use of section 135 and 136 powers and the operation of agreed places of safety in the area, as specified in the Mental Health Act Code of Practice. Decisions on the most appropriate place of safety in individual cases may also be supported by joint police and mental health worker schemes, such as ‘street triage’, where these are in operation.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T10:54:32.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754793/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754793/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance is issued to police officers to make them aware of appropriate places of safety for people detained under section 136 of the Mental Health Act 1983.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","6678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754794","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>The requested information is not held centrally. The way that South Yorkshire Police enforces road traffic law and deploys its available resources are the responsibility of the Chief Constable, taking into account the specific local problems and demands faced by the force.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T09:20:44.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754794/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754794/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Police: South Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police actions were made related to moped use in (a) Barnsley East and (b) South Yorkshire in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","6681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754795","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>Currently the Home Office has four special advisors. One of which is female and one is from an ethnic minority background.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2017-09-05T08:11:40.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754795/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754795/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Home Office: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many special advisers she employs in her Department (a) in total, (b) who are women and (c) who are from ethnic minority backgrounds.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754796","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Premium income generated overseas in 2016/2017 was £124,198,444.07. This represents the Premium element only and does not include the standard application fee. In-country Premium income for the same period was £133,851,555.00. This represents the combined income from the Premium fee and the standard application fee</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T13:23:06.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754796/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754796/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the total fees were that her Department charged for same day visa services in 2016.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754797","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Home Office does not routinely publish the number of premium service applications that take longer than six months to process. The premium service published service standard is to complete 98.5% of straightforward cases on the same day. UKVI transparency data provides details of how the Premium Service Centres perform against that service standard.</p><p> </p><p>A link to the most recent available data is provided here;</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/temporary-and-permanent-migration-data-february-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/temporary-and-permanent-migration-data-february-2017</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T13:28:32.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754797/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754797/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for same day premium visa service have taken longer than six months to process.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754798","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>UKVI transparency data provides details of how the Premium Service Centres perform against that service standard.</p><p> </p><p>A link to the most recent available data is provided here;</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/temporary-and-permanent-migration-data-february-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/temporary-and-permanent-migration-data-february-2017</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T14:19:03.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754798/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754798/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for same day premium visa services were granted on the same day in 2016.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754799","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Home Office publishes information on the number of rapes recorded by the police by the police forces in England and Wales. These figures are published in Table A4 in the Office for National Statistics publication Crime in England and Wales: Year ending March 2017, available here:<a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables</a></p><p>The Home Office does not hold information on the number of people charged with offences of rape. Information on the number of people charged with rape offences is the responsibility of the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS). The CPS publish data on rape in their annual Violence against Women and Girls crime report. The latest publication, for 2015-2016, is available here: <a href="http://www.cps.gov.uk/data/violence_against_women/vawg_2015_16_report.html" target="_blank">http://www.cps.gov.uk/data/violence_against_women/vawg_2015_16_report.html</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","6847","2017-09-05T11:29:23.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754799/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754799/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Rape","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many allegations of rape were reported to the police in each of the last five years in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","6849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754800","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>There was no recruitment campaign for the post of Director-General of UK visas and immigration following the resignation of Sarah Rapson. Mark Thomson, an existing Director General, was appointed to the role on 12<sup>th</sup> September 2016.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T14:14:39.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754800/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754800/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","UK Visas and Immigration: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people applied for the post of Director-General of UK Visas and Immigration  following the resignation of Sarah Rapson.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754801","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Her Majesty’s Passport Office does not monitor or record data on British passport holders who enter or leave the UK. On 31 December 2016, there were 49 million valid UK passports in issue, that were not cancelled, lost or stolen. This data is calculated at the end of each calendar year.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T13:38:05.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754801/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754801/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many British passports are currently in circulation in the UK.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754802","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Home Office publishes information on the number of rapes recorded by the police by the police forces in England and Wales. These figures are published in Table A4 in the Office for National Statistics publication Crime in England and Wales: Year ending March 2017, available here:<a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables</a></p><p>The Home Office does not hold information on the number of people charged with offences of rape. Information on the number of people charged with rape offences is the responsibility of the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS). The CPS publish data on rape in their annual Violence against Women and Girls crime report. The latest publication, for 2015-2016, is available here: <a href="http://www.cps.gov.uk/data/violence_against_women/vawg_2015_16_report.html" target="_blank">http://www.cps.gov.uk/data/violence_against_women/vawg_2015_16_report.html</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","6849","2017-09-05T11:29:23.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754802/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754802/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Rape","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people were charged with the offence of rape in each of the last five years in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","6847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754803","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Home Office is currently drafting a Post legislative Scrutiny Memorandum for the Home Affairs Select Committee on the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012, which will be published as soon as possible after the Home Affairs Select Committee is reconstituted.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-05T08:11:10.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754803/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754803/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Protection of Freedoms Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what post-legislative scrutiny her Department has carried out on the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","6803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754804","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government laid a Written Ministerial Statement in Parliament on Wednesday 12 July 2017, which conveyed the main findings of the review into the funding for Islamist extremist activity in the UK. The review has improved the Government’s understanding of the nature, scale and sources of funding for Islamist extremism in the UK. The Written Ministerial Statement confirms the most significant source of funding for Islamist extremism in the UK is small, private donations from UK-based individuals.</p><p>The review’s report is classified because of the volume of personal information it contains and for national security reasons. The Written Ministerial Statement is a comprehensive and representative reflection of the review’s findings. The Government has no plans to comment further on the review’s findings and it will not provide a running commentary on the groups, individuals or sources it considers to be of extremism concern. The Government’s priority is making the best use of the tools available tools to disrupt extremist activity in the UK.</p><p>The Government concluded a comprehensive review of the Muslim Brotherhood in 2015. The review concluded the movement is a secretive organisation with an ambiguous relationship with violent extremism. The Government remains committed to keeping under review the views promoted and activities undertaken by the Muslim Brotherhood’s associates in the UK, in accordance with the five commitments included in the former Prime Minister’s statement to Parliament.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-05T08:10:51.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754804/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754804/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Muslim Brotherhood: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what conclusions her Department's internal review into the funding of UK Islamist extremist groups has reached on the financing of the Muslim Brotherhood in the UK, including from the State of Qatar; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","6789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754805","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Home Office is currently in discussion with the Metropolitan Police about the problem of motorcycle and moped crime and will look very carefully at the evidence on what more can be done to prevent it.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T11:01:24.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754805/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754805/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Motorcycles: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to reduce the incidence of motorcycle and moped crime in London.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","6796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754806","Home Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>The table below shows the number of UK passports lost during delivery for both the UK and overseas for the last five years.</p><p>Her Majesty’s Passport Office records and cancels any passport lost through delivery, and the customer is issued with a new passport at no extra cost.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Losses</p></td><td><p>Total Volume Printed</p></td><td><p>% Losses against Printed</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>312</p></td><td><p>5,315,465</p></td><td><p>0.006</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>265</p></td><td><p>5,609,530</p></td><td><p>0.005</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>278</p></td><td><p>6,228,867</p></td><td><p>0.004</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>375</p></td><td><p>6,762,898</p></td><td><p>0.006</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>472</p></td><td><p>6,880,927</p></td><td><p>0.007</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-14T15:13:22.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754806/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754806/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Passports: Lost Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passports sent out by the Home Office have been lost in the post in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","6767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754807","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The information requested is not held.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T14:04:26.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754807/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754807/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Passports: Lost Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passports sent in to the Passport Office by members of the public have been lost in the post in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","6766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754808","Home Office","false","2018-02-28","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer given to the Hon. Member for Westmorland and Lonsdale on the 7th February 2017, UIN 60627.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-28T13:10:23.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754808/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754808/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","UK Border Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Border Office staff have been employed in each of the last five years; and what the (a) staffing cost and (b) total cost of the Border Agency has been in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","6764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754809","Home Office","false","2018-01-17","<p>When a customer loses or has a passport stolen while abroad the guidance is that they should report this to the Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office (FCO) where it has been lost. These losses and thefts are recorded by the FCO and the information is passed to Her Majesty’s Passport Office who will take necessary action to cancel the passport as appropriate.</p><p>Previous figures for UK passports lost &amp; stolen outside the UK between 2008-2013 have been published by the FCO:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/foi-release-uk-passports-lost-or-stolen-abroad" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/foi-release-uk-passports-lost-or-stolen-abroad</a></p><p>Other figures published by the FCO relating to lost and stolen passports abroad by British citizens can be found in the attached links:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/passport-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/passport-statistics</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/helping-british-nationals-abroad-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/helping-british-nationals-abroad-2016</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-17T13:18:29.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754809/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754809/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Passports: Lost Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many UK passports have been lost abroad in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","6765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754810","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government’s definition of extremism is set out in the 2015 Counter-Extremism Strategy. The strategy defines extremism as: ‘the vocal or active opposition to our fundamental values including democracy, the rule of law, individual liberty and the mutual respect and tolerance of different faiths and beliefs. We also regard calls for the death of members of our armed forces as extremist.’ The strategy’s definition was used for the review of funding for Islamist extremism in the UK<em>.</em></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-05T08:10:16.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754810/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754810/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what definition her Department used for Islamist extremism for the purposes of its report on the funding of Islamist extremism in the UK.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","6756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754811","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Government has no plans to provide the police with special powers to levy charges in these circumstances.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T11:30:43.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754811/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754811/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Police: Powers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will give the police powers to recover costs from landlords in cases where the police are repeatedly required to deal with drug-related issues at the same premises.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","6769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754812","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government laid a Written Ministerial Statement in Parliament on Wednesday 12 July 2017, which conveyed the main findings of the review into the funding for Islamist extremist activity in the UK. The review has improved the Government’s understanding of the nature, scale and sources of funding for Islamist extremism in the UK.</p><p>The review’s report is classified because of the volume of personal information it contains and for national security reasons. The Written Ministerial Statement is a comprehensive and representative reflection of the review’s findings. The Government has no plans to comment further on the review’s findings and it will not provide a running commentary on the groups, individuals or sources it considers to be of extremism concern. The Government’s priority is making the best use of the tools available to disrupt extremist activity in the UK.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-05T08:11:59.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754812/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754812/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish the list of UK-based Islamist extremist groups identified in the Department's internal review into the funding of Islamist extremist activity in the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","6855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754813","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Since 2010, we have focused on admitting workers who already have a skilled job offer from a sponsoring employer under our Tier 2 visa system, rather than admitting people to look for work. Previous visa routes for jobseekers resulted in many filling low-skilled jobs or remaining unemployed, and were also heavily abused.</p><p>There were 56,051 Tier 2 skilled work visa applications in the year ending March 2017, similar to the level in the previous year. This suggests employers are not experiencing difficulties recruiting candidates directly from overseas for highly skilled roles. Tier 2 ensures that workers are only admitted where employers have demonstrated that a role cannot be filled from the resident labour market. This requirement is waived for recognised shortage occupations, such as doctors in emergency medicine, engineers in the oil and gas industry, and cyber security specialists.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T13:29:43.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754813/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754813/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Visas: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government has made of the potential merits of introducing a visa for jobseekers in higher-skilled roles where employers have demonstrated a difficulty in finding suitable candidates.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","6795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754814","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>Decisions on the size, composition, and deployment of the police workforce are operational matters for the Chief Constable of each area, working with their directly accountable Police and Crime Commissioner.</p><p>We have a constructive and ongoing dialogue with policing about ensuring that the right powers, capabilities and resources are in place to keep the public safe.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-05T10:35:36.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754814/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754814/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of the number of detectives in each police force.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","6362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754815","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government has announced its action plan to tackle the use of acid and other corrosive substances in violent attacks. The action plan includes a review of the law enforcement, criminal justice response, access to harmful products and the support offered to victims. Work is underway and we will be updating MPs in September on the progress made.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-05T08:07:24.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754815/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754815/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Crimes of Violence: Acids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress her Department is making on the review of the legal and criminal justice response to acid attacks.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","6365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754816","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Home Office reviews fees for all UK visa and immigration services on an annual basis, with changes to fees usually implemented on the April common commencement date.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T13:35:55.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754816/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754816/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Visas: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will take steps to review the fees charges for UK visa applications.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","6366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754817","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>Decisions on the size and composition of the workforce including Safer Neighbourhood teams are for the local Chief Constable and the directly accountable Police and Crime Commissioner of each force. It is up to them to decide what the most effective deployment of their resources may be in tackling gang crime and extremist behaviour.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T09:31:53.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754817/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754817/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Safer Neighbourhood Teams","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what effect changes in the size and capacity of Police Safer Neighbourhood teams in England and Wales has had on their capacity to collect intelligence on (a) extremist behaviour and (b) gang crime.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","6355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754818","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>Since 2010, we have sought to minimise the level of bureaucracy imposed on police forces, including through the collection of national data from forces. We have also introduced democratically PCCs to ensure resources are focused on local priorities. The Government is engaging with the police to better understand changes in demand.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-05T11:04:08.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754818/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754818/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 24 April 2017 to Question 71197, on fraud, for what reasons the Government does not assess police spending on each area of demand.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","6356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754819","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The police budget decreased in real terms between 2010 and 2015. It was necessary for the Government to address the deficit and it was right that the police contributed to that.</p><p>Forces have largely risen to the challenge and demonstrated that it is possible to make efficiencies whilst delivering a high quality service to the public. The Government is sensitive to the needs of policing and protected overall police spending in real terms in Spending Review 2015.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-05T10:58:28.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754819/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754819/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 24 April 2017 to Question 71221, whether the police budget has decreased in real terms since 2010.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","6357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754820","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The 2015 Spending Review looked at police funding, including council tax precept. Since Spending Review 2015, we have provided additional flexibility for the 10 Police &amp; Crime Commissioners in England with the lowest precept bills each year (the lower quartile). These PCCS are able to raise their precept by £5 per Band D household, compared to the usual 2%, without triggering a local referendum.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-05T11:15:21.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754820/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754820/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 21 April 2017 to Question 70888, what assessment she has made of the effect of changes to funding to police and crime commissioners on police force budgets in regions where revenue from the council tax precept is relatively low in comparison to other regions in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","6358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754821","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>No decisions have been taken on the police funding formula and no new formula will be introduced without a full public consultation.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-05T11:11:31.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754821/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754821/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 24 April 2017 to Question 71262, on police: finance, what the timescale is for completing the process for reforming the distribution of core grant funding to police force areas.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","6359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754822","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Future decisions about the degree of labour market access that will be made available to EU citizens after the UK leaves the European Union have yet to be determined.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T14:28:07.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754822/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754822/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Agriculture: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her policy is on creating a scheme to facilitate agricultural migrant workers after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Kirstene Hair","Angus","Kirstene Hair","6423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754823","Department for Education","false","2017-09-07","<p>The safeguarding strategy on unaccompanied and refugee children will be published this autumn.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-07T12:26:24.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754823/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754823/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-20","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to publish the safeguarding strategy for unaccompanied asylum-seeking and refugee children.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","6376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754824","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>Government departments have been analysing the UK statute book and directly applicable EU law in their areas of responsibility to enable an assessment of the scale of the changes needed. This is likely to include the repeal, but also the amendment, of provisions in Acts but we are not in a position to give a sense of scale at this time.</p><p> </p><p>In the Government White Paper on the Repeal Bill [‘Legislating for the United Kingdom’s withdrawal from the European Union’], published on 30 March 2017, we estimated around 800 - 1,000 EU-exit related Statutory Instruments will be required.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-05T08:07:01.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754824/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754824/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Home Office: European Union (Withdrawal) Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate her Department has made of the potential number of Acts or parts of Acts that will be subject to repeal as a result of the provisions in the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","6351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754825","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>Fees for firearm and shotgun licences administered by the police were last increased in 2015 so that more of the cost of licensing would be recovered. The fees are currently being reviewed.</p><p>The Government introduced measures, through the Policing and Crime Act 2017, to enable new fees for firearm licences administered by the Home Office and Scottish Government to be set on a cost recovery basis. These were the subject of a public consultation which ran from 12 January to 9 March. We are carefully considering the responses.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T10:58:15.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754825/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754825/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Firearms: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to increase the fees for firearms licences to ensure that the cost of administering the system is covered by the charges.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","6341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754826","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Home Office reviews the data it collects from the police under the Annual Data Requirement on an annual basis, balancing demands for data with the burden of collecting data on the police.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office is presently working with police forces in England and Wales to implement a record level data collection for police recorded crime. This will allow us to investigate linking between the police recorded crime data held by the Home Office and the prosecution and conviction data held by the Ministry of Justice in order to create a richer dataset for analysis.</p><p> </p><p>The arrests data that the Home Office collects from police forces is at the aggregate level rather than record level. Collecting record level data from the police for arrests would result in considerable additional burden on the police and is not currently planned.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T12:28:26.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754826/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754826/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Arrests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 25 April 2017 to Question 71424, whether she has assessed the potential merits of linking data on arrests to prosecution and conviction data.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","6342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754827","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Ipsos Mori survey for HMIC “Public views of policing in England and Wales 2016/17” published on 20 July 2017 shows that: people are most likely to call 999 for crimes/incidents against the person; there is a balance between 999 and 101 for property-related incidents; while for online incidents, anti-social behaviour and updates on previous incidents, 101 is the most likely choice.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T10:56:57.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754827/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754827/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","101 Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the 101 police non-emergency telephone number in reducing public demand on the emergency 999 telephone number.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","6343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754828","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Overall police spending for 2016-17 was £11.6 billion and 2017-18 is £11.9 billion including precept. The vast majority of this funding (over £11bn in 2017-18) is provided directly to democratically elected Police and Crime Commissioners and Chief Constables enabling them to tackle crime, including fraud.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-11T16:49:41.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754828/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754828/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 26 April 2017 to Question 71274, what proportion of the total police budget in England and Wales the £4.6 million outlined in that Answer represents.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","6344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754829","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Police Reform and Transformation Board (PRTB), whose membership is taken from across policing including Police and Crime Commissioners and Chiefs Constables, through a police-led process makes recommendations to the Home Secretary on forces’ bids for the Police Transformation Fund (PTF). The Home Office carries out an assurance exercise before the Home Secretary makes final decisions on funding.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T10:52:24.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754829/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754829/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 26 April 2017 to Question 71274, what process her Department follows to distribute funds from the Police Transformation Fund to police forces in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","6345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754830","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary has recommended that this practice be stopped. The Home Secretary chairs a National Oversight Group to drive a culture change in the police response by ensuring findings from HMIC inspections into domestic abuse are acted upon. HMIC is committed to continuing to inspect the police’s response to domestic abuse and will report on how police forces are responding to its findings.</p><p>The Government has also announced it will bring forward a Domestic Violence and Abuse Bill that will transform the response to domestic abuse.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T10:50:58.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754830/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754830/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 27 April 2017 to Question 71878, on domestic violence, what steps she is taking to address the number of interviews conducted by telephone.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","6338"
